  "prompt": "What are the nutritional differences between lemons and limes?",
  "response": "While both lemons and limes are citrus fruits and share many similarities, there are some subtle nutritional differences between them:\n\n**Overall Similarities:**\n\n*   **Low in Calories:** Both are very low in calories.\n*   **High in Vitamin C:** Excellent sources of vitamin C, an important antioxidant that supports immune function.\n*   **Contain Other Nutrients:** Both contain small amounts of other vitamins and minerals like potassium, vitamin B6, vitamin A, folate, and antioxidants.\n*   **Contain Fiber:** Both contain dietary fiber, though in relatively small amounts.\n*   **Citric Acid:** Both are high in citric acid, which contributes to their tart flavor and may have health benefits.\n\n**Key Differences:**\n\n| Nutrient          | Lemon (Per 100g) | Lime (Per 100g) | Notes                                                       |\n|-------------------|-------------------|-----------------|-------------------------------------------------------------|\n| Calories          | 29 kcal            | 30 kcal          | Very similar                                                 |\n| Carbohydrates     | 9.32 g            | 10.54 g         | Limes slightly higher in carbs                               |\n| Vitamin C         | 53 mg             | 29.1 mg         | **Lemons contain significantly more vitamin C.**               |\n| Calcium           | 26 mg             | 33 mg          | Limes contain slightly more Calcium                             |\n| Potassium         | 138 mg            | 102 mg          | Lemons have higher potassium than limes                        |\n| Vitamin A         | 22 IU             | 20 IU          | Very close, negligible difference                             |\n| Folate (Vitamin B9)| 11 mcg            | 8 mcg           | Lemons have a higher folate content                           |\n| Iron              | 0.6 mg            | 0.6 mg            | Essentially the same                                           |\n| Water             | 89.0 g            | 88.0 g            | Very similar                                                |\n\n**Other Points to Consider:**\n\n*   **Antioxidants:** Both fruits contain various antioxidants like flavonoids. While the specific antioxidant profiles differ slightly, both contribute to overall antioxidant intake.\n*   **Flavor Profile:** This is a major difference! Lemons are generally more tart and have a slightly sweeter flavor, while limes are more acidic and bitter. This flavor difference impacts how they are used in cooking and beverages.\n*   **Variability:** Nutrient content can vary depending on the variety, growing conditions, and ripeness of the fruit.\n\n**Summary:**\n\nWhile both lemons and limes are nutritious citrus fruits, **lemons generally provide more vitamin C and potassium, while limes have slightly more calcium and carbohydrates.** The best choice depends on your individual nutritional needs and, of course, your taste preferences. For boosting vitamin C intake, lemons are slightly more beneficial. For a more distinct, tart flavor, limes might be your preference.  Both are healthy additions to a balanced diet.\n",
